WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.490 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:02.490 --> 00:00:14.470 align:middle line:90%


00:00:14.470 --> 00:00:18.130 align:middle line:84%
>> And here we are, the
granddaddy of all quantum

00:00:18.130 --> 00:00:22.730 align:middle line:84%
weirdness, the infamous
double slit experiment.

00:00:22.730 --> 00:00:25.640 align:middle line:84%
>> The first people who
did these experiments--

00:00:25.640 --> 00:00:28.090 align:middle line:84%
and these experiments
have-- experiments,

00:00:28.090 --> 00:00:31.150 align:middle line:84%
crude experiments of
this kind were first

00:00:31.150 --> 00:00:36.700 align:middle line:84%
performed almost 50 years
ago, or more, 60 years ago.

00:00:36.700 --> 00:00:38.860 align:middle line:90%
Those people were flabbergasted.

00:00:38.860 --> 00:00:40.700 align:middle line:84%
>> To understand
this experiment,

00:00:40.700 --> 00:00:43.600 align:middle line:84%
we first need to
see how particles,

00:00:43.600 --> 00:00:47.110 align:middle line:90%
or little balls of matter, act.

00:00:47.110 --> 00:00:51.280 align:middle line:84%
If we randomly shoot a
small object, say a marble,

00:00:51.280 --> 00:00:55.450 align:middle line:84%
at the screen, we see a
pattern on the back wall

00:00:55.450 --> 00:00:58.720 align:middle line:84%
where they went through
the slit and hit.

00:00:58.720 --> 00:01:02.380 align:middle line:84%
Now, if we add a
second slit, we would

00:01:02.380 --> 00:01:06.250 align:middle line:84%
expect to see a second band
duplicated to the right.

00:01:06.250 --> 00:01:09.140 align:middle line:90%


00:01:09.140 --> 00:01:12.640 align:middle line:90%
Now let's look at waves.

00:01:12.640 --> 00:01:16.390 align:middle line:84%
The waves hit the
slit and radiate out,

00:01:16.390 --> 00:01:20.200 align:middle line:84%
striking the back wall
with the most intensity

00:01:20.200 --> 00:01:23.620 align:middle line:90%
directly in line with the slit.

00:01:23.620 --> 00:01:26.440 align:middle line:84%
The line of brightness
on the back screen

00:01:26.440 --> 00:01:28.760 align:middle line:90%
shows that intensity.

00:01:28.760 --> 00:01:32.260 align:middle line:84%
This is similar to the
line the marbles make.

00:01:32.260 --> 00:01:39.640 align:middle line:84%
But when we had the second slit,
something different happens.

00:01:39.640 --> 00:01:44.830 align:middle line:84%
If the top of one wave meets
the bottom of another wave,

00:01:44.830 --> 00:01:47.500 align:middle line:90%
they cancel each other out.

00:01:47.500 --> 00:01:52.210 align:middle line:84%
So now there is an interference
pattern on the back wall.

00:01:52.210 --> 00:01:56.650 align:middle line:84%
Places where the two tops meet
are the highest intensity,

00:01:56.650 --> 00:01:58.060 align:middle line:90%
the bright lines.

00:01:58.060 --> 00:02:00.830 align:middle line:84%
And where they cancel,
there is nothing.

00:02:00.830 --> 00:02:07.280 align:middle line:84%
So when we throw things, that
is, matter, through two slits,

00:02:07.280 --> 00:02:11.290 align:middle line:90%
we get this, two bands of hits.

00:02:11.290 --> 00:02:14.710 align:middle line:84%
And with waves, we get
an interference pattern

00:02:14.710 --> 00:02:17.260 align:middle line:90%
of many bands.

00:02:17.260 --> 00:02:18.910 align:middle line:90%
Good, so far.

00:02:18.910 --> 00:02:21.385 align:middle line:90%
Now, let's go quantum.

00:02:21.385 --> 00:02:26.840 align:middle line:90%


00:02:26.840 --> 00:02:30.290 align:middle line:84%
>> This is just to break
down your prejudice that says

00:02:30.290 --> 00:02:32.480 align:middle line:90%
a particle is a particle.

00:02:32.480 --> 00:02:34.590 align:middle line:84%
Now we're going to--
you've got to understand

00:02:34.590 --> 00:02:36.410 align:middle line:90%
it's a particle and a wave.

00:02:36.410 --> 00:02:41.480 align:middle line:84%
>> An electron is a
tiny, tiny bit of matter,

00:02:41.480 --> 00:02:44.070 align:middle line:90%
like a tiny marble.

00:02:44.070 --> 00:02:47.660 align:middle line:84%
Let's fire a stream
through one slit.

00:02:47.660 --> 00:02:52.280 align:middle line:84%
It behaves just like the
marble, a single band.

00:02:52.280 --> 00:02:56.910 align:middle line:84%
So if we shoot these tiny
bits through two slits,

00:02:56.910 --> 00:03:01.910 align:middle line:84%
we should get, like
the marbles, two bands.

00:03:01.910 --> 00:03:03.410 align:middle line:90%
What?

00:03:03.410 --> 00:03:05.630 align:middle line:90%
An interference pattern.

00:03:05.630 --> 00:03:10.240 align:middle line:84%
We fired electrons, tiny
bits of matter through.

00:03:10.240 --> 00:03:15.060 align:middle line:84%
But we get a pattern like
waves, not like little marbles.

00:03:15.060 --> 00:03:16.700 align:middle line:90%
How?

00:03:16.700 --> 00:03:20.390 align:middle line:84%
How could pieces of matter
create an interference pattern

00:03:20.390 --> 00:03:22.130 align:middle line:90%
like a wave?

00:03:22.130 --> 00:03:24.320 align:middle line:10%
It doesn't make sense.

00:03:24.320 --> 00:03:27.140 align:middle line:84%
>> You've got to understand,
it's a particle and a wave.

00:03:27.140 --> 00:03:29.480 align:middle line:84%
Now that you've taken
that leap, let's

00:03:29.480 --> 00:03:31.280 align:middle line:84%
get one step closer
to the reality.

00:03:31.280 --> 00:03:34.680 align:middle line:90%
It ain't either of those either.

00:03:34.680 --> 00:03:36.620 align:middle line:90%
And it's both at the same time.

00:03:36.620 --> 00:03:39.360 align:middle line:90%
>> But physicists are clever.

00:03:39.360 --> 00:03:42.020 align:middle line:84%
They thought, maybe
those little balls

00:03:42.020 --> 00:03:45.800 align:middle line:84%
are bouncing off each other
and creating that pattern.

00:03:45.800 --> 00:03:49.790 align:middle line:84%
So they decide to shoot
electrons through one

00:03:49.790 --> 00:03:51.300 align:middle line:90%
at a time.

00:03:51.300 --> 00:03:55.590 align:middle line:84%
There is no way they could
interfere with each other.

00:03:55.590 --> 00:03:58.970 align:middle line:84%
But after an hour of this,
the same interference pattern

00:03:58.970 --> 00:04:00.480 align:middle line:90%
is seen to emerge.

00:04:00.480 --> 00:04:03.360 align:middle line:90%
The conclusion is inescapable.

00:04:03.360 --> 00:04:06.410 align:middle line:84%
The single electron
leaves as a particle,

00:04:06.410 --> 00:04:10.400 align:middle line:84%
becomes a wave of potentials,
goes through both slits,

00:04:10.400 --> 00:04:15.350 align:middle line:84%
and interferes with itself to
hit the wall, like a particle.

00:04:15.350 --> 00:04:17.810 align:middle line:84%
But mathematically,
it's even stranger.

00:04:17.810 --> 00:04:21.779 align:middle line:84%
It goes through both slits
and it goes through neither.

00:04:21.779 --> 00:04:25.640 align:middle line:84%
And it goes through just one and
it goes through just the other.

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:28.790 align:middle line:84%
All of these possibilities
are in superposition

00:04:28.790 --> 00:04:30.080 align:middle line:90%
with each other.

00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:34.250 align:middle line:84%
>> We did these experiments,
and we got certain results.

00:04:34.250 --> 00:04:36.270 align:middle line:84%
And in the light
of these results,

00:04:36.270 --> 00:04:38.600 align:middle line:84%
we asked a question
of the form, gee,

00:04:38.600 --> 00:04:41.900 align:middle line:84%
which path could the electron
have taken through this two

00:04:41.900 --> 00:04:43.297 align:middle line:90%
paths apparatus?

00:04:43.297 --> 00:04:45.860 align:middle line:90%


00:04:45.860 --> 00:04:48.420 align:middle line:84%
And if there are two
options like that,

00:04:48.420 --> 00:04:51.230 align:middle line:84%
it's just a matter of
standard classical logic,

00:04:51.230 --> 00:04:56.060 align:middle line:84%
there are four logical
possibilities, A, B, both,

00:04:56.060 --> 00:04:56.940 align:middle line:90%
neither.

00:04:56.940 --> 00:04:58.880 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:04:58.880 --> 00:05:05.090 align:middle line:84%
We went through those
possibilities one by one

00:05:05.090 --> 00:05:08.570 align:middle line:84%
and designed an
experiment in each case

00:05:08.570 --> 00:05:10.850 align:middle line:90%
to test that possibility.

00:05:10.850 --> 00:05:16.130 align:middle line:84%
And the answer in each of
the four cases was negative.

00:05:16.130 --> 00:05:19.980 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't go through route
A. How do we know that?

00:05:19.980 --> 00:05:23.600 align:middle line:84%
Because when we put in a total
of nothing box in route A,

00:05:23.600 --> 00:05:25.540 align:middle line:84%
it has an effect
on this particle.

00:05:25.540 --> 00:05:29.120 align:middle line:84%
The total of nothing boxes don't
have any effect on particles

00:05:29.120 --> 00:05:30.380 align:middle line:90%
that pass through them.

00:05:30.380 --> 00:05:34.070 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't go through route
B for the same reason.

00:05:34.070 --> 00:05:35.600 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't go
through both routes.

00:05:35.600 --> 00:05:38.060 align:middle line:84%
Because if we stopped the
experiment in the middle,

00:05:38.060 --> 00:05:40.590 align:middle line:84%
we always find it either
on one route or the other,

00:05:40.590 --> 00:05:41.820 align:middle line:90%
but not both.

00:05:41.820 --> 00:05:43.640 align:middle line:84%
And it doesn't
take neither route,

00:05:43.640 --> 00:05:45.770 align:middle line:84%
because if we just
block up the two routes

00:05:45.770 --> 00:05:49.350 align:middle line:84%
and leave everything else
open, nothing gets through.

00:05:49.350 --> 00:05:52.490 align:middle line:84%
So we can systematically,
piece by piece,

00:05:52.490 --> 00:05:58.400 align:middle line:84%
eliminate all of the four
logical possibilities, given

00:05:58.400 --> 00:06:02.000 align:middle line:84%
the assumption that it makes
sense to ask the question,

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:04.100 align:middle line:90%
which route did it take.

00:06:04.100 --> 00:06:06.440 align:middle line:84%
That's how we're forced
into a position, gee,

00:06:06.440 --> 00:06:08.240 align:middle line:90%
the only thing left to do here--

00:06:08.240 --> 00:06:11.870 align:middle line:84%
it's analogous to,
think about the case

00:06:11.870 --> 00:06:16.300 align:middle line:84%
of inquiring into the marital
status of the number 5.

00:06:16.300 --> 00:06:20.020 align:middle line:84%
Somebody says, gee, is
the number 5 married?

00:06:20.020 --> 00:06:22.750 align:middle line:84%
You say, no, that's not
the right thing to say.

00:06:22.750 --> 00:06:26.110 align:middle line:84%
The guy says, I see,
number 5 is a bachelor.

00:06:26.110 --> 00:06:29.380 align:middle line:84%
You say, no, that's
not right either.

00:06:29.380 --> 00:06:33.080 align:middle line:84%
Guy says, well,
what else is there?

00:06:33.080 --> 00:06:36.040 align:middle line:84%
You say, look, the
deal about the number 5

00:06:36.040 --> 00:06:39.550 align:middle line:84%
is, it's not married, it's
not a bachelor, that's

00:06:39.550 --> 00:06:41.450 align:middle line:90%
not a logical contradiction.

00:06:41.450 --> 00:06:43.990 align:middle line:84%
The trouble here is
that the whole question

00:06:43.990 --> 00:06:46.450 align:middle line:84%
of the marital status
of the number 5

00:06:46.450 --> 00:06:50.560 align:middle line:84%
is a question that can't
sensibly be raised.

00:06:50.560 --> 00:06:53.290 align:middle line:84%
That's what we're finding
out about these particles.

00:06:53.290 --> 00:06:55.480 align:middle line:90%
We say, did it take route A?

00:06:55.480 --> 00:06:57.640 align:middle line:84%
We can eliminate
it experimentally.

00:06:57.640 --> 00:06:58.990 align:middle line:90%
Did it take route B?

00:06:58.990 --> 00:07:01.030 align:middle line:84%
We can eliminate
that experimentally.

00:07:01.030 --> 00:07:02.080 align:middle line:90%
Did it take both?

00:07:02.080 --> 00:07:03.350 align:middle line:90%
We can eliminate that.

00:07:03.350 --> 00:07:04.690 align:middle line:90%
Did it take neither?

00:07:04.690 --> 00:07:07.420 align:middle line:90%
We can eliminate that.

00:07:07.420 --> 00:07:10.300 align:middle line:84%
All that leaves us with
is going this route

00:07:10.300 --> 00:07:12.070 align:middle line:90%
that we go with the number 5.

00:07:12.070 --> 00:07:13.420 align:middle line:90%
Oh, I see.

00:07:13.420 --> 00:07:15.460 align:middle line:84%
Although in this case,
it's astonishing.

00:07:15.460 --> 00:07:18.490 align:middle line:84%
With the case of the
number 5, it was easy.

00:07:18.490 --> 00:07:21.370 align:middle line:84%
What this must be telling
us is that it somehow

00:07:21.370 --> 00:07:24.130 align:middle line:84%
fails to make
sense even to raise

00:07:24.130 --> 00:07:27.230 align:middle line:84%
the question in a
situation like this,

00:07:27.230 --> 00:07:28.780 align:middle line:84%
which route did
the particle take?

00:07:28.780 --> 00:07:31.420 align:middle line:84%
>> Physicists were
completely baffled by this,

00:07:31.420 --> 00:07:36.700 align:middle line:84%
so they decided to peek and
see which slit it actually goes

00:07:36.700 --> 00:07:38.270 align:middle line:90%
through.

00:07:38.270 --> 00:07:41.160 align:middle line:84%
They put a measuring
device by one slit

00:07:41.160 --> 00:07:46.450 align:middle line:84%
to see which one it went
through and let it fly.

00:07:46.450 --> 00:07:49.720 align:middle line:84%
But the quantum world
is far more mysterious

00:07:49.720 --> 00:07:51.790 align:middle line:90%
than they could have imagined.

00:07:51.790 --> 00:07:55.480 align:middle line:84%
When they observed,
the electron went back

00:07:55.480 --> 00:07:57.550 align:middle line:84%
to behaving like
a little marble.

00:07:57.550 --> 00:08:01.930 align:middle line:84%
It produced a pattern of two
bands, not an interference

00:08:01.930 --> 00:08:04.030 align:middle line:90%
pattern of many.

00:08:04.030 --> 00:08:09.160 align:middle line:84%
The very act of
measuring, or observing,

00:08:09.160 --> 00:08:12.100 align:middle line:84%
which slit it went
through meant it only

00:08:12.100 --> 00:08:15.630 align:middle line:90%
went through one, not both.

00:08:15.630 --> 00:08:20.850 align:middle line:84%
The electron decided
to act differently,

00:08:20.850 --> 00:08:26.310 align:middle line:84%
as though it was aware
it was being watched.

00:08:26.310 --> 00:08:28.680 align:middle line:84%
>> So the electron
is very peculiar.

00:08:28.680 --> 00:08:30.570 align:middle line:84%
Electron is very
peculiar in the sense

00:08:30.570 --> 00:08:33.600 align:middle line:84%
that when you are not
looking, electron can be here,

00:08:33.600 --> 00:08:35.850 align:middle line:84%
can be there, or it
can be over there,

00:08:35.850 --> 00:08:37.740 align:middle line:90%
in the corner of this room.

00:08:37.740 --> 00:08:41.809 align:middle line:84%
It can be all over this
storm, so to speak.

00:08:41.809 --> 00:08:45.310 align:middle line:84%
But whenever we look,
this is the strange thing

00:08:45.310 --> 00:08:46.680 align:middle line:90%
about this electron.

00:08:46.680 --> 00:08:49.140 align:middle line:84%
So whenever we
look, we always find

00:08:49.140 --> 00:08:53.220 align:middle line:84%
them to be in one
particular Geiger counter.

00:08:53.220 --> 00:08:56.130 align:middle line:84%
Although we may have a room
full of Geiger counters,

00:08:56.130 --> 00:09:01.530 align:middle line:84%
we never hear the Geiger counter
sticking all over the room.

00:09:01.530 --> 00:09:04.200 align:middle line:84%
This is the fundamentally
important stuff

00:09:04.200 --> 00:09:05.910 align:middle line:90%
about the electrons.

00:09:05.910 --> 00:09:09.480 align:middle line:84%
>> It was here that
physicists stepped forever

00:09:09.480 --> 00:09:13.900 align:middle line:84%
into the strange never
world of quantum events.

00:09:13.900 --> 00:09:16.130 align:middle line:90%
What is matter?

00:09:16.130 --> 00:09:18.370 align:middle line:90%
Marbles or waves?

00:09:18.370 --> 00:09:20.620 align:middle line:90%
And waves of what?

00:09:20.620 --> 00:09:26.050 align:middle line:84%
And what does an observer
have to do with any of this?

00:09:26.050 --> 00:09:33.370 align:middle line:84%
The observer collapsed the wave
function simply by observing.

00:09:33.370 --> 00:09:39.180 align:middle line:90%


00:09:39.180 --> 00:09:42.560 align:middle line:90%
>> We are always the observer.

00:09:42.560 --> 00:09:46.190 align:middle line:84%
But sometimes we
identify with the event

00:09:46.190 --> 00:09:50.840 align:middle line:84%
so much so that we even lose
the aspect of the observer.

00:09:50.840 --> 00:09:53.253 align:middle line:84%
That's why the materialist
gets totally lost

00:09:53.253 --> 00:09:55.295 align:middle line:84%
and thinks that we could
do without the observer.

00:09:55.295 --> 00:09:59.390 align:middle line:90%


00:09:59.390 --> 00:10:04.680 align:middle line:84%
>> The physics data tells us
that an object itself is really

00:10:04.680 --> 00:10:08.840 align:middle line:84%
a simplification for
what we call out there,

00:10:08.840 --> 00:10:12.510 align:middle line:84%
what is particularly when we're
looking at atomic and subatomic

00:10:12.510 --> 00:10:16.680 align:middle line:84%
particles, or atomic and
subatomic matter in any form.

00:10:16.680 --> 00:10:19.530 align:middle line:84%
What we find is how
we go to look at it,

00:10:19.530 --> 00:10:21.900 align:middle line:84%
what we choose to
examine it with,

00:10:21.900 --> 00:10:25.140 align:middle line:84%
actually changes the
properties of what

00:10:25.140 --> 00:10:26.670 align:middle line:90%
we observe to be out there.

00:10:26.670 --> 00:10:31.620 align:middle line:84%
>> Is this the observer,
and which is so intricate

00:10:31.620 --> 00:10:36.540 align:middle line:84%
to understanding the wacky,
weird world of quantum

00:10:36.540 --> 00:10:41.540 align:middle line:90%
particles and how they react?

00:10:41.540 --> 00:10:46.850 align:middle line:90%
Is this then the observer?

00:10:46.850 --> 00:10:51.920 align:middle line:84%
And even though we cannot
have a quantum field without

00:10:51.920 --> 00:10:56.300 align:middle line:84%
the observation of scientists
who have gone there,

00:10:56.300 --> 00:10:59.870 align:middle line:84%
who have uncovered it, layer
after layer after layer,

00:10:59.870 --> 00:11:02.650 align:middle line:90%
they're all observers.

00:11:02.650 --> 00:11:06.640 align:middle line:84%
But not one of them
agree conclusively

00:11:06.640 --> 00:11:10.180 align:middle line:84%
on all points in the
field, because they

00:11:10.180 --> 00:11:13.870 align:middle line:84%
are perceiving the
field mathematically

00:11:13.870 --> 00:11:16.440 align:middle line:84%
from different
angles of perception.

00:11:16.440 --> 00:11:22.960 align:middle line:10%
>> Mathematics shows us clearly
that the movement of objects

00:11:22.960 --> 00:11:28.360 align:middle line:10%
are describable only in
terms of possibilities,

00:11:28.360 --> 00:11:32.590 align:middle line:10%
not the actual events that
happens in our experience.

00:11:32.590 --> 00:11:36.160 align:middle line:10%
Quantum physics calculates
only possibilities,

00:11:36.160 --> 00:11:40.240 align:middle line:10%
that if we accept this, then
the question immediately comes,

00:11:40.240 --> 00:11:43.210 align:middle line:10%
who, what chooses among
these possibilities

00:11:43.210 --> 00:11:46.400 align:middle line:10%
to bring the actual
event of experience.

00:11:46.400 --> 00:11:50.980 align:middle line:84%
So we directly, immediately
see that consciousness must be

00:11:50.980 --> 00:11:54.180 align:middle line:84%
involved. the observer
cannot be ignored.

00:11:54.180 --> 00:11:58.690 align:middle line:84%
Observer is part of the
description of the world.

00:11:58.690 --> 00:12:02.560 align:middle line:84%
But the observer is not
included in quantum physics.

00:12:02.560 --> 00:12:07.630 align:middle line:84%
We can only describe the
objects, not the subject.

00:12:07.630 --> 00:12:13.640 align:middle line:84%
So we get the idea that
the subject must be more

00:12:13.640 --> 00:12:16.160 align:middle line:90%
fundamental than the objects.

00:12:16.160 --> 00:12:17.960 align:middle line:84%
Consciousness is
more fundamental.

00:12:17.960 --> 00:12:20.660 align:middle line:84%
>> We don't know, in
quantum mechanics,

00:12:20.660 --> 00:12:25.590 align:middle line:84%
how to hook ourselves as
observers up with the world.

00:12:25.590 --> 00:12:28.070 align:middle line:84%
We don't know how
